        modelAnswer: `Slovakia is a small, landlocked country in Central Europe with a population of approximately 5.5 million people. It borders the Czech Republic, Austria, Hungary, Ukraine, and Poland. The capital is Bratislava, situated on the Danube river near the Austrian border. The country is characterised by a mountainous north — including the High Tatras, the highest mountain range in the Carpathians — and a flatter, agricultural south. Slovakia joined the European Union in 2004 and adopted the Euro in 2009. It's a parliamentary republic with a President and Prime Minister.

For tourists, I would particularly recommend the High Tatras for stunning mountain scenery and hiking. Bratislava has a charming old town, the castle, and vibrant café culture. Spiš Castle — one of Europe's largest — is spectacular and a UNESCO World Heritage site. Banská Štiavnica, a historic mining town, is also UNESCO listed. Bojnice Castle is a fairy-tale romantic castle. The Slovak Paradise national park offers beautiful gorges and waterfalls. Čičmany village has unique traditional painted wooden houses.

Slovak customs include strong family traditions, celebrating name days almost as much as birthdays, and the distinctive Easter Monday tradition of boys pouring water on girls and using willow whips — symbolising health and fertility. Christmas is celebrated on December 24th with carp and potato salad. Folk traditions — music, dance, embroidery, and craft — are still actively preserved.

Important historical figures include Ľudovít Štúr, who codified the Slovak literary language in the 19th century, giving Slovaks a national identity through language. Milan Rastislav Štefánik was an astronomer, general, and diplomat who co-founded Czechoslovakia. Alexander Dubček led the Prague Spring in 1968 — an attempt at humanising communism that was crushed by Soviet invasion. Štefan Banič, a Slovak immigrant in the USA, invented the parachute in 1913.`
