        bullets: [
          "Talk about the events and personalities that influenced the development of English.",
          "Name some words in English of different origins.",
          "Point out some differences between British and American English.",
          "Why is it necessary to learn English?"
        ],
        modelAnswer: `English is a fascinating language with a remarkably complex history. Old English developed from the Germanic dialects brought to Britain by Anglo-Saxon invaders in the 5th and 6th centuries. The Viking invasions added Norse elements. The Norman Conquest of 1066 brought an enormous influx of French vocabulary — and this is why English today has such pairs as "begin" (Germanic) and "commence" (French). The Renaissance introduced thousands of Latin and Greek words into the language. Shakespeare, writing in the late 16th and early 17th centuries, coined or popularised hundreds of words and phrases we still use today — "bedroom," "lonely," "break the ice." The British Empire spread English globally, and American English developed its own distinct character through the 18th–20th centuries.

English contains words from an extraordinary number of languages: "ketchup" from Malay, "algebra" from Arabic, "sofa" from Turkish, "piano" from Italian, "kindergarten" from German, "ballet" from French, "yacht" from Dutch, "chocolate" from Nahuatl (Aztec). This borrowing reflects English's contact with cultures worldwide.

British and American English differ in spelling (colour/color, theatre/theater), vocabulary (biscuit/cookie, lift/elevator, trousers/pants, flat/apartment), pronunciation (particularly vowel sounds and stress patterns), and some grammatical constructions. Neither is "correct" — they're both valid varieties of the language.

Why learn English? It is the global lingua franca — the language of international business, science, academia, aviation, and diplomacy. Knowing English opens access to the world's largest body of knowledge, literature, and cultural content. It dramatically increases employment opportunities in a globalised economy. It enables travel and genuine cultural connection. For Slovaks, it's the most practically useful language to master alongside Slovak. In short — it's not a luxury, it's an essential skill for full participation in the modern world.`
